FIG. 1 is a block diagram showing a general configuration example of a spectrum analyzer;


FIG. 2A is a diagram showing a display example of a spectrum wave form in a C/N measurement;


FIG. 2B is a diagram showing a display example of a spectrum wave form in a intermodulation distortion measurement;


FIG. 3A is a diagram showing a relationship between a fundamental wave level and a third order distortion level;


FIG. 3B is a diagram showing a relationship between the levels when an input attenuation amount is increased by ATT from the state of FIG. 3A;


FIG. 4A is a diagram showing an input/output characteristic of a frequency mixer for a fundamental wave and a third order distortion;


FIG. 4B is a diagram for explaining an intercept point;


FIG. 5A is a diagram showing a display example of a spectrum wave form in an S/N measurement;


FIG. 5B is a diagram showing a display example in which a spectrum wave form is displayed on a left half portion of a screen and a noise changing state on a time axis is displayed on a right half portion of the screen;


FIG. 6A is a diagram showing a characteristic between a frequency interval of a displayed wave form and a noise level (an input dynamic range), the characteristic having parameters of band widths RBW of a band pass filter;


FIG. 6B is a diagram showing a measurable region in the characteristic diagram of FIG. 6A;


FIG. 7 is a flow chart showing a sequence of an S/N measurement.


FIG. 8A is a diagram showing an example of a burst wave input;


FIG. 8B is a diagram showing a trigger synchronized with a burst wave;


FIG. 8C is a diagram showing a gate signal for signal acquisition;


FIG. 8D is a diagram showing an example of a burst wave on a display screen and an example of a signal acquisition range;


FIG. 9 is a flow chart showing a control sequence of an input attenuation amount for obtaining an intercept point; and


FIG. 10 is an overall flow chart of a measuring method by a spectrum analyzer.
